In terms of treatment type, the market for chronic ocular surface pain offers a variety of options to manage and alleviate symptoms. Artificial tears play a crucial role in lubricating the eyes and providing relief from dryness, making them a popular choice among patients. Additionally, punctal plugs are gaining traction as an effective solution to maintain moisture on the ocular surface by blocking tear drainage. The use of anti-inflammatory drugs, autologous serum eye drops, and other treatment modalities further contribute to the diverse landscape of therapeutic interventions available to patients with chronic ocular surface pain.

The end-users of chronic ocular surface pain treatments encompass a range of healthcare settings, including hospitals, clinics, and ambulatory surgical centers. These facilities play a vital role in the diagnosis, management, and treatment of patients with severe ocular conditions, offering a comprehensive approach to care that includes advanced treatment modalities and surgical interventions when necessary. Hospitals, in particular, serve as key providers of specialized care for individuals suffering from chronic ocular surface pain, ensuring access to the latest technologies and treatment options.

